## 2. Definitions and Terminology

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Artificial Intelligence (AI)** | A machine-based system that can, for a given set of human-defined objectives, make predictions, recommendations, decisions, or generate content, influencing real or virtual environments |
| **Machine Learning (ML)** | A subset of AI where systems improve performance through exposure to data without being explicitly programmed for each task |
| **Generative AI (GenAI)** | AI models capable of producing novel content (text, code, images, data) based on training data and user prompts |
| **GxP** | A collective term for Good Practice guidelines regulated by health authorities (e.g., GMP, GCP, GLP, GDP) requiring data integrity, traceability, and system validation |
| **AI Risk Classification** | A tiered categorization (Critical, High, Medium, Low) assigned to an AI system based on its potential impact on patient safety, data integrity, or regulatory compliance |
| **Human-in-the-Loop (HITL)** | A design principle ensuring human oversight and approval is embedded in AI decision workflows, particularly for high-stakes outputs |
| **Model Drift** | The degradation of an AI model's predictive accuracy over time due to changes in underlying data patterns |
| **Bias (AI)** | Systematic errors in AI outputs arising from skewed training data, flawed design assumptions, or unrepresentative model evaluation |
| **Validation (AI/ML)** | The documented process of verifying that an AI system performs its intended function reliably, consistently, and within defined parameters |
| **Audit Trail** | An automated, time-stamped electronic record of actions taken within or by an AI system, enabling traceability and accountability |
| **CAPA** | Corrective and Preventive Action — a structured process for investigating deviations and implementing sustainable fixes |
| **SaMD** | Software as a Medical Device — AI/ML software intended to perform medical diagnosis, treatment, or monitoring functions |

